<br>
Warrior - 38.9% Mitigation, 53.6% Avoidance (3424 total)<br>
Monk - 32.5% Mitigaion, 69.8% Avoidance (1729 total)<br>
<br>
<br>
That means if a mob hits for 100 max lets say, you found warrior to get hit for 61.9 as the average hit, and the monk to get hit for 67.5 as the average hit.<br>
<br>
53.6% avoidance means that 46.4% of all attempted hits landed for the warrior.<br>
69.8% avoidance meanst that 30.2% of all attempted hits landed for the monk.<br>
<br>
So average hit including misses for the warrior is 61.9 X 46.4% = 28.7<br>
Average hit including misses for the monk is 67.5 X 30.2% = 20.4<br>
<br>
Warrior gets hit for 28.7 on average, and the monk gets hit for 20.4 on average.  This is a very limited, probably skewed (due to lack of data points) test made by a monk, but it shows that monks take 20.4 / 28.7 = 71% of the damage a warrior takes against these mobs.  You could also say a monk tanks 28.7 / 20.4 = 41% better than a warrior.<br>
<br>
Still not seeing why Verant thought this nerf was neccessary? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uconentenderheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Conen Tenderheart</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://cgof.freeservers.com/images/trans-piccolo2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 67<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/10/02 9:16:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ran some tests</span><hr size=1>  Actually no I do not see the need for the nerf.<br>
